<HEADLINE>
<P>
MOVE OF OCEANSIDE SOUP KITCHEN OKD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RAY TESSLER7/26/90 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Brother Benno's soup kitchen in Oceanside has won city approval to move from 
downtown, where it has caused controversy, to an industrial area near the 
Oceanside Municipal Airport. 
</P>
<P>
The Planning Commission voted, 7-0, Monday night to let the 6-year-old kitchen 
relocate and begin new services, including job counseling, showers, a day room 
and substance abuse therapy. 
</P>
<P>
However, the commission required Brother Benno's, which is run by a nonprofit 
foundation, to follow strict rules to make sure its patrons do not loiter 
around nearby businesses. 
</P>
<P>
Despite receiving acclaim, the existing Brother Benno's kitchen on Minnesota 
Street, where 225 dinners a night are served, has drawn criticism that drunks 
and loiterers have burglarized and littered. RAY TESSLER 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA072690-0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 252414 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
July 26, 1990, Thursday, South Bay Edition 
</P>
