<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN GABRIEL VALLEY DIGEST: ALHAMBRA; 
</P>
<P>
WATER-SAVING PLAN ADOPTED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The City Council on Monday adopted a three-phase water conservation plan, 
effective immediately. 
</P>
<P>
In the first, voluntary phase, residents are urged to follow a number of 
water-saving measures. 
</P>
<P>
The second phase makes those measures mandatory. The third is a rationing 
phase, which requires that residents cut water use by a percentage based on the 
severity of the drought. 
</P>
<P>
Water-saving measures include not hosing sidewalks and driveways, not serving 
drinking water in public places, watering lawns only during the evening and 
night, repairing leaky faucets and sprinkler systems, and not filling swimming 
pools, spas and hot tubs. 
</P>
<P>
Assistant City Manager Terry L. James said the city is in the first phase and 
will proceed to the mandatory phase if the water table in the San Gabriel Basin 
doesn't rise by September or October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
