<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY DIGEST: SOUTH GATE; 
</P>
<P>
COUNCIL CITES SAFETY IN BAN ON ICE CREAM VENDORS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The South Gate City Council has unanimously approved an amendment to its 
ordinance banning ice cream push carts. 
</P>
<P>
The amendment adds a restriction to keep vendors off city streets because of 
traffic hazards they might create, officials say. 
</P>
<P>
City law already prohibits pushcart vendors who are unable to obtain health 
permits from the Los Angeles County Health Department, City Administrator Bruce 
Spragg said. 
</P>
<P>
Spragg said some vendors recently received health permits, but the council 
wanted to continue banning them from the city. 
</P>
<P>
The council sees this as a public safety issue, the administrator said. The 
carts are especially dangerous for children who run into the streets to buy ice 
cream, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
